Interesting that you put this content out there. The idea that some goverments put bureaucracy and obstacles for people to travel feels to me like an abuse on the part of the governments. The right to move freely, and to make a living wherever anyone is, is a personal basic right. Yet governments ban this all over. It's an abuse to lock a place and tell an individual you cannot enter. Earth belongs to everyone. Of course it is hard when someone has ill intentions, but for this we need to address the issue differently, instead of banning all population from a specific country to travel. Specially when policies are made with all sort of personal interests and where a country can be banned just because another country has specific interests in the resources of said country, or just wants to discredit said country.

"Powerful" countries stay powerful in the same way that rich people stay rich. They create systems that allow them to keep those positions, no matter what. They win, the rest lose. By doing this they keep the gap with the other countries wide. There's inequality. And there's usually no desire to close that gap. Inspite of the diplomacy saying the opposite. Those are usually false words like those of the politicians and corporate owners that have ambitious goals to reduce climate change.

Hundreds of years ago people from european countries (French, German, Portuguese, Spaniards, edit: just realized I forgot to add English) travelled the world. Went almost everywhere, "conquering" other countries. They got there, wiped out populations, cultures, believes, languages. They brought with them diseases that killed hundreds of indigenous peoples. Yet these very same countries ban the entry now to the population from those countries they invaded so many years ago. Countries they extracted their resources, richeness, treasures, even people. Countries they left with such deep wounds. And as far as I know they haven't even been repaid or at least apologized for. Rarely even acknowledged.


So this idea of banning people from traveling, feels like such a ... hipocrisy when looking at their own past, such lack of acknowledging the world belongs to all beings, to respect, to own in the sense of taking care of them. And what we need to heal is the fear, the disconnection, the anger, the pain. Not to break the natural bonds that are created when people travel.

This explanation is really oversimplified... As a matter of fact, there is generally no such thing as visa-free entry for foreign citizens, there's usually only visa-free entry for a very short time period and with lots of other restrictions. You will usually need a visa if you need more than that. Even with this reservation in mind, what's counted as visa-free access in the tables such as shown in this video can in fact be an electronic visa based entry, e.g. in order to enter Australia or the US you need to fill out an electronic application, pay a fee and wait for travel authorization, sometimes you will be required to pass an interview. On the other hand, once you get a mutiple entry Schengen visa, you don't need to get individual visas to enter ~30 countries including Schengen members and non-Schengen members which allow entry with a Schengen visa.

I suggest that you recalculate your table assuming that for visa related purposes all Schengen members are a single entity and "visa-free access" with obligatory travel authorization is more like visa on arrival than real "visa-free".

Well, the coronavirus is not exactly the best example - Polish citizens, as they are EU citizens as well, have been safely evacuated back to Europe by the French. Under certain conditions, EU citizens are entitled to seek help from any EU member state embassy, they're not strictly limited to their own country. And as shown by the coronavirus example, EU member states will likely cooperate in cases of international emergencies. So yeah, while Poland may not be exactly the most powerful country in the EU, at least as long as it keeps being a member, its passport will be pretty strong for all travel-related purposes.
